english:
  title: A Record of the Luo City Wall of Sichuan
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: 'The Luo City Wall of Sichuan stands four ren high, three xun broad, with a circumference of thirty-three li. It was built by the present-day Huai-Hai Grand General Yan Gong. Sichuan, a realm apart from Liang Province, stands as the mighty capital of the Shu Kingdom. Within, it borders the territories of Jian and Yue; without, it connects to the Barbarian lands. On the left it overlooks the hundred Pu peoples; on the right it neighbors the six Rong tribes. A critical throat controlling vast exchanges, yet bonds with the distant center prove fragile as lips and teeth. Since ancient times, divine turtles have left their miraculous traces here. When first a city was built to defend this frontier, the four outer walls remained incomplete. The rulers of old sought to seal it tight; the people yearned to flee elsewhere. Those savage tribes, wild as wolves, would descend whenever grass withered on the Bao roads and the Lu River ran low, their topknots streaming behind their assault. Common folk trembled in terror; streets echoed with lament. Garrison commanders relied on flying banners for their strategy; magistrates deemed closed gates their best counsel. Thus calamity accumulated through the years. When the Qianfu era dawned, the bonds suddenly snapped. Great rebellion erupted. The White Tiger''s mad destruction grew fierce; the old Yellow Dragon''s covenant faded. With military force exhausted and imperial heart uncertain, this exceptional general emerged—one versed in the classics of war, tested through battles in distant Jiao-zhi where eight imperial decrees proclaimed his valor, proven in ruling Yun-cheng where peace was restored in less than three years. When barbarian raids intensified and the royal army withdrew, an urgent summons flew to the east. Thus he rode forth, his single chariot advancing day and night from distant lands—no need for the sage Gong Sui to offer counsel; no hesitation in accepting his command mid-journey. Arriving at Xian-yang, he received his appointment as Commander of Western Sichuan, bearing the emperor''s subtle wisdom. Swift as thought, he reached Cheng-du. Then, with Biao Xin''s forces encamped but thirty li from the gates, the people had lost their livelihoods and ten thousand households lay burned to ash. The enemy marshaled their full might while we cowered behind closed gates, suffering devastation. Outside blazed a fire that could not be quenched; within, the springs had run dry. Yet when this general arrived and swung wide the city gates like opening a cage, his mere presence extinguished all aggression. The barbarian king, whose ears had caught wind of his extraordinary stratagems, trembled like one witnessing lightning and thunder. His warriors scattered like startled birds and fleeing fish. The general then dispatched elite troops in brief pursuit, leveraging their moment of flight to display our overwhelming force. Countless prisoners were taken; the defeated beyond measure. Thereafter, studying maps and discovering nature''s strongholds—the mountain lairs of gibbons, the hidden paths of wolves—he established a supreme fortress and mighty bulwarks. He repaired the Gorge Gate, established the Peace-Bringing garrison. The barbarians'' vital routes were now firmly sealed, worry vanished. Steep ramparts rose using mountain slopes for height; long moats drew upon flowing streams for depth. A perfect mechanism of defense, blocking every secret passage. Clay pressed tight would hold; none could breach these walls. With signal fires blazing, no battle need be fought—victory came through mere presence. He also opened waterway routes, establishing new river fortifications. By the Great Crossing River, he placed the River Defense Camp. Distant raiders lost all means of passage; those who once caused suffering now dared not even speak of approach. The frontier became stable as an overturned bowl; households prospered. Counselors composed verses; local lords accumulated wealth in peace. Though the general dreamed of leisurely boats upon the rivers, he saw that lasting peace required lasting walls. Thus he declared: "The barbarian nature is deceptive—constant change like morning and evening. Though even the mightiest warriors vanquish their foes, future threats always linger. How can we merely name this the Brocade City without building the great wall? The defense of our people falls to me alone. Present this plan with sincerity, and heaven itself will aid; submit this memorial, and the emperor will grant approval." His advisors demurred, offering doubts. "When Gongsun Shu rode forth boldly and Zhuge Liang emerged from seclusion, they had grand purposes. Yet when Zhang Yi of old built the inner city, he had to transport soil from distant mountains, laboring nine long years to complete it. How can we now, with no native earth, finish such works without endless delay?" The general replied: "The plan is already fixed; the work must proceed swiftly. It shall satisfy heaven''s will—do not doubt what seems impossible." Thus the county magistrate hastened to report, the prefect eagerly complied. They measured heights and depths, calculated resources, consulted the Spring and Autumn Annals for timing, and followed the Zhou Rituals for design. Channeling the long river, they carved trenches that would shame Yu the Great; raising high walls, they eclipsed even Qin Shihuang''s ambitions. Five divine beings directed labor; six magical forces drove the work. Water spirits supplied the springs; earth deities transformed sand to fertile soil. In Shu''s land, though springs surge from the shallowest dig, here earth emerged from the sand itself, and the walls hardened as if they had always been. Truly the hundred spirits aided in secret; ten thousand people labored with joy. Spades rose like clouds; pestles thundered like thunder. No storms hindered the work; all feasted well. Voices rose in cheering; walls seemed to leap skyward. A hundred sections were completed; thirty days saw it finished. Then the craftsmen''s skill rendered poor materials fine; artisans'' genius made red earth shimmer. Beacon towers pierced the sky; fortress walls soared upward. Eight gates opened in the towers, their glazed tiles shone with flying phoenixes in colors bright; railings spanned all quarters, their embroidered parapets hung with rainbows on clear days. One river''s beauty was embraced; ten thousand households'' joy contained. From afar, it rose like layered peaks amid clouds, ringed by rosy mist and glimmering haze. Drawing near, it gleamed like the celestial mountains of the sea''s edge, with golden platforms and silver palaces luminous between. From first gathering the workers to final completion, not one coin was drawn from imperial treasury, not one grain from military stores. The construction cost one hundred fifty thousand strings of cash and nineteen thousand bushels of rice—all provided through wise management from surplus revenues alone. Thus was created this magnificent sight. The barbarian chiefs lost their nerve; even distant peoples turned their hearts toward us. None dared approach our walls; none could mount assault. The general had the works painted and presented to the nine-fold heaven. The emperor sent back words of praise beyond measure, commanding the Hanlin scholars to compose an inscription. The stele erected to commemorate this achievement bears words composed by Zu-yong, Wang the Prime Minister. Though the general received the emperor''s gifts, he would not raise a stone tablet—such was his humility, his shame at sudden fame. Yet when the emperor later toured these walls in person and witnessed their strength, his heart grew ever more secure. Beholding them directly, he held the general''s loyalty ever dearer, commanding that an inscription be carved in stone to proclaim these deeds for all eternity. Never before in ten thousand years has such honor been bestowed; nowhere under heaven exists its equal. How beautiful it is! The dragon needs clouds to rise; the fish need water to be merry. Who does not look up to a general whose wisdom foresees all things, whose actions accord with opportunity like keys fitting locks? In ages past, Shu had no such wall, as heaven preserved this great deed, waiting each day for an extraordinary man. For extraordinary men bring forth extraordinary deeds; extraordinary deeds bring forth extraordinary achievements. Thus the extraordinary transcends what ordinary people can even perceive. Though I, Chi-won, gaze toward the halls of the sage yet see nothing—a blind man among masters—still, even the state of Qin did not cast aside talents like You Yu. So I have carefully recorded these true events, daring to inscribe this singular achievement. May the four seas traverse these roads and bow before such might; may the nine regions'' soldiers gaze upon the imperial progress and find peace. Written on the twenty-fifth day of the eighth month of the year Guiji in the third year of Zhonghe.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yan Gong (燕公): A historical military commander under the Tang Dynasty, specifically serving during the reign of Emperor Xizong. This work celebrates his construction of defensive fortifications around Sichuan.'
  - key: ''
    value: The five divine beings and six magical forces referenced here are terms from Chinese cosmology and military strategy texts, representing the coordination of supernatural and natural forces in the massive construction project.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhang Yi (張儀): A historical figure from Warring States period known for his diplomatic and military achievements. The anecdote about transporting soil from Jing-she Mountain (淨射山) to build the inner city of Chengdu reflects historical records of ancient Sichuan construction challenges.'
  - key: ''
    value: Zhonghe third year (中和三年) corresponds to 883 CE, placing this work in the late Tang Dynasty period of significant frontier military activity.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Brocade City' (錦城) is a classical epithet for Chengdu, capital of Sichuan, referring to its prosperity in silk production.
